05933nam a22010215i 9780691222660DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912226607 a10.1515/97806912226602doi  a(DE-B1597)585059  a(OCoLC)1291506684  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a738.30938/52231 aArrington, Nathan T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAthens at the Margins :bPottery and People in the Early Mediterranean World /cNathan T. Arrington. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b138 b/w illus., 16 color illus. (8-page insert)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tChapter 1. The Margins -- tChapter 2. From Phaleron Ware to Exotica: A Historiography of Protoattic -- tChapter 3. The Place of Athens in the Mediterranean: Horizons and Networks -- tChapter 4. Interaction at the Grave: Style, Practice, and Status -- tChapter 5. Artists and Their Styles: Production, Process, and Subjectivity -- tChapter 6. Drinking and Worshipping Together: Participation and Subjectivity in the Symposium and the Sanctuary -- tChapter 7. Back to Phaleron -- tTable 1: Protoattic Burials -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow the interactions of nonelites influenced Athenian material culture and societyThe seventh century BC in ancient Greece is referred to as the Orientalizing period because of the strong presence of Near Eastern elements in art and culture. Conventional narratives argue that goods and knowledge flowed from East to West through cosmopolitan elites. Rejecting this explanation, Athens at the Margins proposes a new narrative of the origins behind the style and its significance, investigating how material culture shaped the ways people and communities thought of themselves.Athens and the region of Attica belonged to an interconnected Mediterranean, in which people, goods, and ideas moved in unexpected directions. Network thinking provides a way to conceive of this mobility, which generated a style of pottery that was heterogeneous and dynamic. Although the elite had power, they were unable to agree on the norms of conspicuous consumption and status display. A range of social actors used objects, contributing to cultural change and to the socially mediated production of meaning. Historiography and the analysis of evidence from a wide range of contexts—cemeteries, sanctuaries, workshops, and symposia—offers the possibility to step outside the aesthetic frameworks imposed by classical Greek masterpieces and to expand the canon of Greek art.Highlighting the results of new excavations and looking at the interactions of people with material culture, Athens at the Margins provocatively shifts perspectives on Greek art and its relationship to the eastern Mediterranean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPottery, GreekzGreecezAthens. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aAthens.  aAttica.  aDaidalos and the Origins of Greek Art.  aEarly Archaic Greece.  aGreek archaeology.  aGreek art.  aKerameikos.  aLevant.  aOrientalizing.  aPhaleron cemetery.  aPhaleron style.  aProto-attic symposion.  aProto-attic symposium.  aProtoattic pottery.  aProtoattic symposion.  aProtoattic symposium.  aS. P. Morris.  aThe Black and White Style.  aUn art citoyen.  aceramics.  acult cultural history.  aelite mobility networks.  apolis attribution.  apottery.  aseventh century.  aseventh-century Athens.  aseventh-century art.  aseventh-century burials.  a